tegory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/J002720/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The starting point for this research is a focus on some fundamental features of human behaviour, namely its extreme flexibility coupled with goal directedness. It is for cognitive control to ensure that the appropriate action is performed in a given context, and this issue of control of task set can be investigated in the laboratory using task-switching paradigms. A striking phenomenon in such paradigms is the substantial cost to performance (longer RTs, more errors) of a change of task, the switch cost, which can be reduced by the opportunity to prepare but is normally not entirely eliminated by preparation.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research investigates phenomena related to this residual cost, and also looks at the reduction in switch cost obtained with different degrees of preparation. The aim is to develop a real-time computational model, which is able to account for phenomena related to the residual cost, including my own dataset. In this way it is hoped to isolate particular components of the residual switch cost and generate further experimental means of enquiry into this phenomenon. This model should also help to explain the most typical ERP modulations found in task-switching studies (the preparation related switch positivity and the post-stimulus switch negativity).&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2013-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2012-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>71699</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This research examined a fundamental feature of human behavior, its flexibility coupled with goal directedness. Cognitive control ensures that the appropriate action is performed in a given context such as when we have to switch from performing one task to the next. But behavior can also be determined by stimuli in the environment triggering a certain action automatically. This is attributed to learning of associations between stimuli and certain actions over time. This research asked the question to what extend performance when switching between tasks can be explained by associative (automatic) processes. We reported first evidence for switch costs (performance decrements on task switches compared to repeats) in a situation where subjects had no knowledge of the tasks but instead had learned simple stimulus-response associations. We were able to predict performance under these conditions with an APECS connectionist model based on back-propagation. We recorded brain potentials for a group of subjects that performed the experiment under explicit task instructions and a group that was given cue-stimulus-response (CSR) mappings. When the task group was given a task cue and time to prepare they showed the typical brain activity previously reported in preparation for a switch (which has been taken as marker of proactive control). Interestingly, for a short time during the preparation interval the CSR group showed similar brain activity although they had no notion of the tasks. In sum, these results suggests that low-level associative processes underlie human cognition and contribute to performance even in situations where performance was thought to be predominantly guided by executive control. The implication of this is that there might be other ways to achieve behavioural change than training the executive control system. This is a promising avenue because it is known that for example stress consistently compromises the resource limited control system up to the point that control fails. Findings of this research contributed ideas to a project on behavioural change, which was recently funded by the ERC for five years.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The research conducted during this grant increased knowledge of the processes involved in switching tasks which may lead to a greater understanding in ergonomics, human-computer interaction, management research and other domains of application, stimulating both field and experimental studies on the costs of switching between tasks in the workplace, errors in critical contexts, stress and individual differences in competence. It further contributed to the question of how to achieve behavioural change (e.g., healthier eating habits, avoiding substance abuse, etc..) by highlighting alternatives to cognitive control.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>209DA2AC-9897-42FB-A142-ABE3E1D26DD2</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>54637b2955fdc4.91112670</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Education,Financial Services, and Management Consultancy,Healthcare,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><g